  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT347-kilavi">poruḷ valikkum neñciṟkut talaimakaṉ collic celavaḻuṅkiyatu. </p>


        <p xml:lang="en">HE dispensing with going, speaking to [his] heart that
          strives after wealth. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT347">
          <l> malkucuṉai pularnta nalkūr curamutaṟ</l>
          <l> kumari vākaik kōluṭai naṟuvī</l>
          <l> maṭamāt tōkaik kuṭumiyiṟ ṟōṉṟuṅ</l>
          <l> kāṉa nīḷiṭait tāṉu nammō</l>
          <l> ṭoṉṟumaṇañ ceytaṉa ḷivaḷeṉiṉ</l>
          <l> ṉaṉṟē neñca nayantaniṉ ṟuṇivē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent2">When [you] consider that she has made the one <note place="foot"> What is conveyed by <term xml:lang="ta">oṉṟu </term>? Is this the one, decisive union? Or an adverbial "once"?       </note> union</l>
        <l rend="indent">with us, also she herself, <note place="foot"> Does <term xml:lang="ta"> tāṉ-um </term> emphasize HER part in the undertaking, that is, she has done it out of her own free will?    </note> on the long forest way, <note place="foot"> The rest probably should be connected with <term xml:lang="ta"> eṉiṉ </term>, not with <term xml:lang="ta"> ceytaṉaḷ </term>, that is, when HE is on his way his heart thinks of the one he has left behind. </note>
    </l>
    <l rend="indent2">where the stalked <note place="foot"> Why the pronounced <term xml:lang="ta"> -uṭai </term>? The blossom sticks out just like the crest of the peacock, because the stalks are so long?   </note> fragrant blossom of the maiden Sirissa</l>
  <l rend="indent2">appears like the crest of a youthful big peacock,</l>
  <l rend="indent">in the poor desert, where plentiful mountain pools have dried up,</l>
  <l>– good [is], heart, your decision that you longed for. <note place="foot"> Namely, to judge from the situation of this interior monologue in the desert (and contrary to the <term xml:lang="ta"> kiḷavi </term>, which reads the whole as taking place before setting out), the decision to return to HER. The direct object to <term xml:lang="ta"> nayanta </term> supplemented by Cām., <term xml:lang="ta"> poruḷ </term>, would give a different note: in spite of HIS sympathetic(?) memory of HER, who has stayed behind, he moves on. </note>
</l>

<lg type="alternate" sameAs="5b" resp="#TVG">
  <l>If you considered that she would make the one union with us <note place="foot"> T.V.G. reads in accordance with the <term xml:lang="ta"> kiḷavi </term>, namely a hypothetical request to the heart to take HER along when going – which is impossible and implicitly means HE is not willing to go at all. This does not seem to pay attention to the peculiar <term xml:lang="ta"> oṉṟu maṇam </term>.  </note></l>

</lg>
</lg>

</div>
</body>
